>It's Okay to Be Boring on Christmas
Impregnation is probably my #1 fetish so it really hurts to say that the story falls off a cliff towards the end. The buildup is fantastic but the “I love you knock me up now” at the end just feels like it wastes it and introduces some elements to Carnation's character that get more disturbing the more you think about them. The love at first sight I can get, but the whole “seriously planning to get pregnant” part tips over from “charmingly impulsive” to a split between “outright psycho” and “dangerously impulsive”. She met anon mere hours ago on rebound from rejection and her reaction to modest romance is “aww yeah, time to get knocked up”. Her being a virgin, which yes I know “if she’s not a virgin she’s slut trash”, clashes with her extreme sexual impulse too. The car teasing I can get in the sense of her not going further than that, but when her first response to being treated slightly better than garbage is “make me pregnant” it becomes unbelievable. Are we supposed to expect that anon is literally the only person in the world who finds her pretty and has spent a night complementing her? I know it’s the fantasy but it breaks immersion hard.
I also get it’s for the fun of Christmas babies, but I feel like the story would flow a lot better if they had fairly normal passionate sex, and then had a timeskip to the following year for her to try for kids. Or maybe I’m just reading way too much into this and the impregnation bit is meant to just be an impulsive risk thing playing off her character, but it’s taken way too seriously by anon and the narration for that. Maybe throwing in some of her earlier nervousness and some mild freaking out over having had breeding sex with her new boyfriend right off the bat, followed by anon giving the classic “well if it did get you pregnant I’ll still stick with you” sort of lines, would make the baby names and wife-calling come off more charming

Well, don't take this the wrong way.
If you like the idea, have at it yourself. Most of the writers here already have ongoing projects. But if you're willing to put in the time to do the work...
Let's start slapping together an outline for you.
Is said female lead an existing Beastars character or do you have an idea or two for an OC?
Anon gets isekaied. What are his three qualities that help him get past the initial shock? What quality nearly gets him injured/killed, potentially trapping him there or creating an antagonist for him?
Why would anyone help him? What kind of help to they offer, and why?
How does he meet the female lead? What are her initial impressions? Does anyone else know about this encounter, and what are their (less informed) opinions?
Where might the human male find a niche? Is this in opposition to anyone he now knows, thus creating tension to show off how the world works?
Let's say these the most tenuous attraction between the two leads. How are they creating more threads to connect them to each other?

This just a few of the pretty basic questions I'd ask, whether it's a isekai based story, a cookie-cutter Hallmark Christmas romance, or a Hollywood romcom.
Give yourself the chance to try. Writers and artist learn by doing, usually because ideas won't leave them be. Like love, you sometimes have to throw yourself out the plane and catch the parachute on the way down.
